Scope of the Standard

Shunyaya True Logic (STL) defines a deterministic structural collapse-governance layer over classical Boolean evaluation.

STL establishes:

Finite structural truth space:

T5 = {Z0, Eplus, S, Eminus, Zstar}

Deterministic structural operators:

NOT_s
AND_s
OR_s

Collapse mapping:

phi_T(S) = TRUE
phi_T(Zstar) = FALSE
phi_T(Z0) = UNDEFINED
phi_T(Eplus) = UNDEFINED
phi_T(Eminus) = UNDEFINED

Replay-verifiable determinism

Structural admissibility discipline

STL does not:

modify Boolean logic
modify domain equations
introduce predictive models
simulate system dynamics
perform optimization
guarantee safety outcomes

STL governs collapse admissibility, not causation.


Conformance

An implementation conforms to the STL Open Standard if it:

Preserves Boolean logic under collapse:

For stable endpoints:

phi_T(op_s(A,B)) = op_bool(phi_T(A), phi_T(B))
when A,B in {S, Zstar}

Produces deterministic classification over T5.

Defines structural operators closed over T5.

Produces byte-identical artifacts under independent replay:

B_A = B_B

Avoids probabilistic or tolerance-based arbitration.

Any implementation introducing:

randomness
probabilistic inference
adaptive tuning
tolerance-based collapse
nondeterministic output

does not conform to the STL Open Standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.


